Name: DIBUTYL SEBACATE
Description: Dibutyl decanedioate is a fatty acid ester.

environmental_bioconcentrations.References: (1) Riddick JA et al; Organic Solvents: Physical Properties and Methods of Purification 4th ed NY, NY: Wiley Interscience (1986) (2) Lyman WJ et al; Handbook of Chemical Property Estimation Methods. Washington, DC: Amer Chem Soc pp. 5-3 (1990) (3) Franke C et al; Chemosphere 29: 1501-14 (1994)
environmental_bioconcentrations.Value: An estimated BCF of 77 was calculated for dibutyl sebacate(SRC), using a water solubility of 40 mg/l(1) and a regression-derived equation(2). According to a classification scheme(3), this BCF suggests the potential for bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low(SRC).

environmental_biodegradations.References: (1) Osmon JL et al; pp. 66-75 in Proc Int Biodeterior Symp. 2nd (1972) (2) Klausmeier RE, Jones WA; Dev Ind Microbiol 2: 47-53 (1960)
environmental_biodegradations.Value: Dibutyl sebacate was degraded by pure bacterial and fungal cultures over 1 to 4 week incubation periods in shake flask experiments(1). Pure strains of the fungus Fusarium were shown to degrade dibutyl sebacate and several other plasticizers(2).

non_human_toxicity_excerpts.References: Clayton, G.D., F.E. Clayton (eds.) Patty's Industrial Hygiene and Toxicology. Volumes 2A, 2B, 2C, 2D, 2E, 2F: Toxicology. 4th ed. New York, NY: John Wiley & Sons Inc., 1993-1994., p. 3042
non_human_toxicity_excerpts.Value: ...In a 2 yr period study, dietary levels of 0.25, 1.25, and 6.25% dibutyl sebacate were fed to rats. The data showed no weight, hematologic, or bone marrow changes, but some isolated inflammatory changes in the lungs, some nephrosis and fatty livers at the highest dose.

non_human_toxicity_excerpts.References: Clayton, G.D., F.E. Clayton (eds.) Patty's Industrial Hygiene and Toxicology. Volumes 2A, 2B, 2C, 2D, 2E, 2F: Toxicology. 4th ed. New York, NY: John Wiley & Sons Inc., 1993-1994., p. 3042
non_human_toxicity_excerpts.Value: Toxicologic data indicate that the material is practically nontoxic orally or by dermal contact.

non_human_toxicity_excerpts.References: Lefaux, R. Practical Toxicology of Plastics. Cleveland: CRC Press Inc., 1968., p. 362
non_human_toxicity_excerpts.Value: ORAL /ACUTE/ TOXICITY. DOSES OF 1-32 G/KG BODY WT WERE ADMIN TO YOUNG RATS 5-10 WK OLD & WEIGHING 60-75 G. ALL DOSES UP TO 16 G/KG WERE TOLERATED... DOSES OF 4-8 G/KG BODY WT WERE ADMIN TO RATS IM WITHOUT PRODUCING ANY OBSERVABLE REACTIONS.

soil_absorption_mobility.References: (1) Riddick JA et al; Organic Solvents: Physical Properties and Methods of Purification. 4th ed NY, NY: Wiley Interscience (1986) (2) Lyman WJ et al; Handbook of Chemical Property Estimation Methods. Washington, DC: Amer Chem Soc pp. 4-5 (1990) (3) Swann RL et al; Res Rev 85: 17-28 (1983)
soil_absorption_mobility.Value: The Koc of dibutyl sebacate is estimated as 575(SRC), using a water solubility of 40 mg/l(1) and a regression-derived equation(2). According to a classification scheme(3), this estimated Koc value suggests that dibutyl sebacate is expected to have low mobility in soil(SRC).
